# Lists & Navigation - Building Data-Driven Interfaces

## 1. Understanding Lists in SwiftUI (60 min)

### What are Lists?
- **Container views** that display rows of data
- Similar to UITableView but **much simpler**
- Automatically handles **scrolling, selection, and styling**
- Built on top of SwiftUI's declarative syntax

### Basic List Syntax:
```swift
List {
    Text("Row 1")
    Text("Row 2")
    Text("Row 3")
}
```

### Lists with Arrays:
```swift
let fruits = ["Apple", "Banana", "Orange"]

List(fruits, id: \.self) { fruit in
    Text(fruit)
}
```

### Why Lists are Powerful:
- **Automatic recycling** (like UITableView reuse)
- **Smooth performance** with large datasets
- **Built-in gestures** and interactions
- **Consistent styling** across iOS

## 2. Building Basic Lists (60 min)

### Static Lists:
```swift
List {
    Text("Settings")
    Text("Profile")
    Text("Notifications")
    Text("Help")
}
```

### Dynamic Lists from Arrays:
```swift
struct TodoItem: Identifiable {
    let id = UUID()
    let title: String
    let isCompleted: Bool
}

let todos = [
    TodoItem(title: "Buy groceries", isCompleted: false),
    TodoItem(title: "Walk the dog", isCompleted: true),
    TodoItem(title: "Learn SwiftUI", isCompleted: false)
]

List(todos) { todo in
    HStack {
        Image(systemName: todo.isCompleted ? "checkmark.circle.fill" : "circle")
        Text(todo.title)
    }
}
```

### Mixed Static and Dynamic Content:
```swift
List {
    Section(header: Text("Favorites")) {
        Text("Starred Items")
        Text("Recent")
    }

    Section(header: Text("All Items")) {
        ForEach(items) { item in
            Text(item.name)
        }
    }

    Section(footer: Text("End of list")) {
        Button("Load More...") {
            // Load more action
        }
    }
}
```

## 3. Navigation Fundamentals (60 min)

### NavigationView Basics:
- **Container** for navigable content
- Provides **navigation bar** and **hierarchy management**
- Automatically handles **back buttons** and **transitions**

### Basic Navigation Setup:
```swift
NavigationView {
    List {
        Text("Home Screen")
        Text("Profile Screen")
        Text("Settings Screen")
    }
    .navigationTitle("Main Menu")
}
```

### NavigationLink - The Navigation Trigger:
```swift
NavigationView {
    List {
        NavigationLink("Go to Details") {
            Text("Detail Screen")
        }

        NavigationLink(destination: Text("Another Screen")) {
            HStack {
                Image(systemName: "star")
                Text("Favorites")
            }
        }
    }
    .navigationTitle("Navigation Demo")
}
```

### Navigation Modifiers:
```swift
.navigationTitle("My App")          // Large title
.navigationBarTitleDisplayMode(.large) // .large or .inline
.navigationBarHidden(false)           // Show/hide bar
.navigationBarBackButtonHidden(false) // Show/hide back button
```

## 4. Combining Lists & Navigation (60 min)

### Typical App Pattern:
```swift
struct ContentView: View {
    let categories = ["Tech", "Sports", "Food", "Travel"]

    var body: some View {
        NavigationView {
            List(categories, id: \.self) { category in
                NavigationLink(destination: CategoryDetail(category: category)) {
                    HStack {
                        Image(systemName: "folder")
                        Text(category)
                        Spacer()
                        Text("5 items")
                            .foregroundColor(.gray)
                    }
                }
            }
            .navigationTitle("Categories")
        }
    }
}

struct CategoryDetail: View {
    let category: String

    var body: some View {
        List {
            Text("Item 1 in \(category)")
            Text("Item 2 in \(category)")
            Text("Item 3 in \(category)")
        }
        .navigationTitle(category)
    }
}
```

### Passing Data Between Screens:
```swift
struct User: Identifiable {
    let id = UUID()
    let name: String
    let email: String
}

struct UserListView: View {
    let users = [
        User(name: "John Doe", email: "john@example.com"),
        User(name: "Jane Smith", email: "jane@example.com")
    ]

    var body: some View {
        NavigationView {
            List(users) { user in
                NavigationLink(destination: UserDetailView(user: user)) {
                    VStack(alignment: .leading) {
                        Text(user.name)
                            .font(.headline)
                        Text(user.email)
                            .font(.subheadline)
                            .foregroundColor(.gray)
                    }
                }
            }
            .navigationTitle("Users")
        }
    }
}

struct UserDetailView: View {
    let user: User

    var body: some View {
        VStack(alignment: .leading, spacing: 16) {
            Text(user.name)
                .font(.largeTitle)
            Text(user.email)
                .font(.title2)
                .foregroundColor(.blue)
            Spacer()
        }
        .padding()
        .navigationTitle("User Details")
        .navigationBarTitleDisplayMode(.inline)
    }
}
```

## 5. Advanced List Features (60 min)

### List Sections:
```swift
List {
    Section(header: Text("Important")) {
        Text("Urgent Task")
        Text("Critical Update")
    }

    Section(header: Text("Regular"), footer: Text("End of regular tasks")) {
        ForEach(regularTasks) { task in
            Text(task.title)
        }
    }

    Section(header: Text("Completed")) {
        Toggle("Show completed", isOn: $showCompleted)
        if showCompleted {
            ForEach(completedTasks) { task in
                Text(task.title)
                    .strikethrough()
                    .foregroundColor(.gray)
            }
        }
    }
}
.listStyle(InsetGroupedListStyle())
```

### List Styles:
```swift
.listStyle(PlainListStyle())           // Basic full-width
.listStyle(GroupedListStyle())         // iOS 13 grouped
.listStyle(InsetGroupedListStyle())    // iOS 14+ inset grouped
.listStyle(SidebarListStyle())         // For sidebar navigation
```

### Swipe Actions (iOS 15+):
```swift
List {
    ForEach(todos) { todo in
        Text(todo.title)
            .swipeActions(edge: .trailing) {
                Button("Delete", role: .destructive) {
                    deleteTodo(todo)
                }

                Button("Edit") {
                    editTodo(todo)
                }
                .tint(.blue)
            }
            .swipeActions(edge: .leading) {
                Button("Complete") {
                    completeTodo(todo)
                }
                .tint(.green)
            }
    }
}
```

### Pull to Refresh:
```swift
List(items) { item in
    Text(item.name)
}
.refreshable {
    await loadData()
}
```

## 6. Navigation Patterns & Best Practices (60 min)

### Programmatic Navigation:
```swift
struct ContentView: View {
    @State private var isShowingDetail = false
    @State private var selectedItem: String? = nil

    var body: some View {
        NavigationView {
            List {
                Button("Show Detail Programmatically") {
                    selectedItem = "Manual Selection"
                    isShowingDetail = true
                }

                NavigationLink(
                    "Go to Detail", 
                    destination: Text("Detail Screen"),
                    isActive: $isShowingDetail
                )
            }
            .navigationTitle("Programmatic Nav")
        }
    }
}
```

### Navigation Stack Management:
```swift
.navigationBarItems(
    leading: Button("Cancel") { /* action */ },
    trailing: HStack {
        Button("Edit") { /* action */ }
        Button("Add") { /* action */ }
    }
)
```

### Tab-Based Navigation with Lists:
```swift
TabView {
    NavigationView {
        List {
            // Home content
        }
        .navigationTitle("Home")
    }
    .tabItem {
        Image(systemName: "house")
        Text("Home")
    }

    NavigationView {
        List {
            // Settings content
        }
        .navigationTitle("Settings")
    }
    .tabItem {
        Image(systemName: "gear")
        Text("Settings")
    }
}
```

### Common Navigation Patterns:
- **Master-Detail**: List â†’ Detail screen
- **Tab-Based**: Multiple main sections
- **Hierarchical**: Deep navigation trees
- **Modal**: Temporary screens on top

## Practice Exercises

Complete all exercises to master Lists & Navigation in SwiftUI!

