# Grids & Layout - Creating Responsive UI

## 1. Introduction to Grid Systems (30 min)

**Grids** are fundamental to creating organized, responsive layouts in SwiftUI. Unlike stacks that arrange views in a single direction, grids allow two-dimensional layouts.

### Why Use Grids?
- **Responsive Design**: Automatically adapt to different screen sizes
- **Consistent Spacing**: Maintain uniform spacing between elements
- **Complex Layouts**: Create magazine-style, gallery, or dashboard layouts
- **Performance**: Lazy grids only create views as needed

## 2. LazyVGrid - Vertical Grids (60 min)

### Basic LazyVGrid Structure:
```swift
LazyVGrid(columns: columns, alignment: .center, spacing: 20) {
    ForEach(items, id: \.self) { item in
        ItemView(item: item)
    }
}
```

### GridItem Types:
- **`.flexible()`**: Shares available space equally
- **`.adaptive(minimum:)`**: Creates as many columns as fit
- **`.fixed(CGFloat)`**: Fixed width columns

### Column Configurations:
```swift
// Three equal columns
let threeColumns = [
    GridItem(.flexible()),
    GridItem(.flexible()),
    GridItem(.flexible())
]

// Responsive columns (2-4 based on screen size)
let responsiveColumns = [
    GridItem(.adaptive(minimum: 150))
]

// Mixed column types
let mixedColumns = [
    GridItem(.fixed(100)),    // Fixed sidebar
    GridItem(.flexible()),    // Flexible content
    GridItem(.fixed(80))      // Fixed actions
]
```

## 3. LazyHGrid - Horizontal Grids (45 min)

### Basic LazyHGrid Structure:
```swift
LazyHGrid(rows: rows, alignment: .center, spacing: 15) {
    ForEach(items, id: \.self) { item in
        ItemView(item: item)
    }
}
```

### Row Configurations:
```swift
// Two equal rows
let twoRows = [
    GridItem(.flexible()),
    GridItem(.flexible())
]

// Fixed height rows
let fixedRows = [
    GridItem(.fixed(80)),
    GridItem(.fixed(120)),
    GridItem(.fixed(80))
]
```

## 4. Advanced Grid Features (45 min)

### Grid Alignment Options:
```swift
// Different alignments for different use cases
LazyVGrid(columns: columns, alignment: .leading)  // Left-aligned
LazyVGrid(columns: columns, alignment: .trailing) // Right-aligned
LazyVGrid(columns: columns, alignment: .center)   // Center-aligned
```

### Pinned Views (Headers/Footers):
```swift
LazyVGrid(columns: columns, pinnedViews: [.sectionHeaders]) {
    Section(header: HeaderView()) {
        ForEach(items) { item in
            ItemView(item: item)
        }
    }
}
```

## 5. Responsive Design Patterns (60 min)

### Adaptive Layouts:
```swift
@State private var gridColumns = [GridItem(.adaptive(minimum: 160))]

var body: some View {
    LazyVGrid(columns: gridColumns) {
        ForEach(items) { item in
            ItemView(item: item)
        }
    }
    .onAppear {
        // Adjust based on screen size
        updateGridLayout()
    }
}
```

### Orientation Changes:
```swift
// Detect orientation changes
@State private var isLandscape = false

private var gridLayout: [GridItem] {
    if isLandscape {
        return [GridItem(.adaptive(minimum: 200))]
    } else {
        return [GridItem(.adaptive(minimum: 160))]
    }
}
```

## 6. Performance Optimization (30 min)

### Why Lazy Grids?
- **Memory Efficient**: Only create visible views
- **Fast Scrolling**: Smooth performance with large datasets
- **Dynamic Loading**: Load data as user scrolls

### Best Practices:
```swift
// Good: Lazy loading with identifiable data
LazyVGrid(columns: columns) {
    ForEach(items, id: \.id) { item in
        ItemView(item: item)
            .onAppear { loadMoreIfNeeded(item) }
    }
}

// Avoid: Complex views in grid cells
LazyVGrid(columns: columns) {
    ForEach(items) { item in
        // Keep grid cells simple!
        SimpleItemView(item: item)
    }
}
```

## 7. Real-World Examples (30 min)

### Photo Gallery:
```swift
struct PhotoGallery: View {
    let photos: [Photo]
    let columns = [GridItem(.adaptive(minimum: 100))]

    var body: some View {
        ScrollView {
            LazyVGrid(columns: columns, spacing: 2) {
                ForEach(photos) { photo in
                    AsyncImage(url: photo.url) { image in
                        image.resizable().scaledToFill()
                    } placeholder: {
                        Color.gray
                    }
                    .frame(height: 100)
                    .clipped()
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
```

### Dashboard Layout:
```swift
struct Dashboard: View {
    let stats: [StatItem]
    let columns = [
        GridItem(.flexible()),
        GridItem(.flexible())
    ]

    var body: some View {
        LazyVGrid(columns: columns, spacing: 16) {
            ForEach(stats) { stat in
                StatCard(stat: stat)
                    .frame(height: 120)
            }
        }
        .padding()
    }
}
```

